Alexis Castillo-Soto of the UK’s Department for Education went on to say ‘Selling that concept isn’t easy and only an innovative service will convince the sceptics’. Castillo-Soto was previewing his session on enhancing the business environment with personal technology – but the quotation can be easily repositioned in the world of external information supply in the business environment. It prompts the question ‘What is the core mission of an external information specialist in today’s world?’ BIR identifies four important strands of this mission:


To stimulate innovation;



To increase the productivity of knowledge workers – now the majority of the workforce;



To enable organizations to take soundly-based decisions that reflect the direction of their current and potential external environment and take advantage of their own knowledge and experience – this includes the opportunities in business intelligence;



And, of course, to operate cost effectively.

Each of these strands provides a route for business information professionals to deliver best value to their organizations from investments in business information personnel and content.
